**John McCarthy**

A titan of the digital age, John McCarthy (September 4, 1927 – October 24, 2011) was an American computer scientist and cognitive scientist whose work fundamentally shaped the trajectory of computing. He is widely recognized as one of the principal architects of [artificial intelligence](/Artificial_intelligence) (AI), a discipline he helped to define and establish. McCarthy was part of an exclusive cadre of researchers in the 1950s and 1960s who laid the groundwork for what would become a transformative field. His intellectual contributions were vast, ranging from coining the very term "artificial intelligence" in the seminal proposal for the [Dartmouth workshop](/Dartmouth_workshop) to developing the influential [Lisp](/Lisp_(programming_language)) family of symbolic programming languages. Beyond these cornerstones, his innovations extended to popularizing [time-sharing](/Time-sharing) systems, a concept that revolutionized how humans interacted with computers, and inventing [garbage collection](/Garbage_collection_(computer_science)), a fundamental technique for automatic memory management.

McCarthy spent the majority of his illustrious career at [Stanford University](/Stanford_University), where his influence permeated the academic landscape and fostered generations of pioneering thinkers. His profound impact on the field of AI was acknowledged with numerous prestigious accolades, including the 1971 [Turing Award](/Turing_Award), often referred to as the "Nobel Prize of Computing," for his groundbreaking contributions to AI. He also received the United States [National Medal of Science](/National_Medal_of_Science), the highest honor for scientific achievement in the U.S., and the esteemed [Kyoto Prize](/Kyoto_Prize) for his multifaceted intellectual contributions.

### Early Life and Education

Born in [Boston, Massachusetts](/Boston,_Massachusetts), on September 4, 1927, John McCarthy's lineage traced back to an Irish immigrant father and a [Lithuanian Jewish](/Lithuanian_Jewish) immigrant mother. The family's journey during the turbulent [Great Depression](/Great_Depression) saw frequent relocations, eventually settling in [Los Angeles, California](/Los_Angeles,_California), where his father found work as an organizer for the [Amalgamated Clothing Workers](/Amalgamated_Clothing_Workers). His father hailed from [Cromane](/Cromane), a picturesque fishing village in [County Kerry](/County_Kerry), Ireland. His mother passed away in 1957.

During the 1930s, both of McCarthy's parents were active members of the [Communist Party](/Communist_Party_USA), fostering an environment that encouraged intellectual curiosity and rigorous critical thinking. Even before entering high school, McCarthy’s fascination with science was ignited by a Russian popular science book for children, "100,000 Whys." His early proficiency in the [Russian language](/Russian_language) facilitated friendships with Russian scientists during his travels to the [Soviet Union](/Soviet_Union). However, his perspective shifted following subsequent visits to the [Soviet Bloc](/Soviet_Bloc), leading him to adopt a more [conservative](/Conservatism_in_the_United_States) political stance and align with the [Republican Party](/Republican_Party_(United_States)).

McCarthy demonstrated exceptional academic promise early on, graduating from [Belmont High School](/Belmont_High_School_(Los_Angeles)) two years ahead of schedule. His admission to Caltech in 1944 was a testament to his precocious intellect. He possessed a remarkable aptitude for [mathematics](/Mathematics), self-teaching himself college-level material by studying textbooks from the nearby [California Institute of Technology](/California_Institute_of_Technology) (Caltech) during his teenage years. This allowed him to bypass the initial two years of mathematics coursework upon enrollment. His academic career at Caltech was briefly interrupted by a suspension for neglecting [physical education](/Physical_education) requirements. After serving in the [US Army](/US_Army), he was readmitted and earned his Bachelor of Science ([BS](/Bachelor_of_Science)) in [mathematics](/Mathematics) in 1948.

A pivotal moment in his intellectual development occurred at Caltech when he attended a lecture by the renowned mathematician [John von Neumann](/John_von_Neumann), an encounter that profoundly inspired his future research directions.

McCarthy pursued his graduate studies at Caltech before transitioning to [Princeton University](/Princeton_University). There, under the mentorship of [Donald C. Spencer](/Donald_C._Spencer), he obtained his [PhD](/PhD) in mathematics in 1951, with his dissertation focusing on "[Projection operators](/Projection_(linear_algebra))" and [partial differential equations](/Partial_differential_equation).

### Academic Career

Following brief teaching appointments at Princeton and [Stanford University](/Stanford_University), McCarthy accepted a position as an assistant professor at [Dartmouth College](/Dartmouth_College) in 1955.

A year later, in the autumn of 1956, he moved to [MIT](/MIT) as a research [fellow](/Fellow). During his tenure at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT), his students affectionately began referring to him as "Uncle John."

In 1962, McCarthy ascended to the rank of full [professor](/Professor) at Stanford, a position he held until his retirement in 2000. Throughout his academic life, McCarthy was a fervent advocate for the application of mathematics, including [lambda calculus](/Lambda_calculus), to the nascent field of artificial intelligence, particularly in developing logics capable of achieving [common sense](/Commonsense_reasoning) in AI systems.

### Contributions in Computer Science

John McCarthy stands as one of the foundational figures in the field of artificial intelligence, alongside luminaries such as [Alan Turing](/Alan_Turing), [Marvin Minsky](/Marvin_Minsky), [Allen Newell](/Allen_Newell), and [Herbert A. Simon](/Herbert_A._Simon). It was McCarthy, along with Minsky, [Nathaniel Rochester](/Nathaniel_Rochester_(computer_scientist)), and [Claude E. Shannon](/Claude_E._Shannon), who proposed the term "artificial intelligence" in their influential proposal for the landmark [Dartmouth conference](/Dartmouth_workshop) held in the summer of 1956. This conference is widely considered the birthplace of AI as a distinct academic discipline. Minsky would later join McCarthy at MIT in 1959, solidifying their collaborative influence.

In 1958, McCarthy put forth the concept of the [advice taker](/Advice_taker), a theoretical system designed to ingest knowledge and make logical deductions, which served as a significant inspiration for subsequent research in question-answering systems and [logic programming](/Logic_programming).

During the late 1950s, McCarthy made a crucial discovery: primitive recursive functions could be extended to handle symbolic expressions, a breakthrough that led to the creation of the [Lisp programming language](/Lisp_(programming_language)). This seminal paper on functional programming also introduced the lambda notation, drawn from the syntax of [lambda calculus](/Lambda_calculus), which would later influence the semantic underpinnings of dialects like [Scheme](/Scheme_(programming_language)). Lisp rapidly became the dominant programming language for AI research following its publication in 1960.

In 1958, McCarthy played a key role on an [Association for Computing Machinery](/Association_for_Computing_Machinery) ad hoc committee on programming languages. This committee was instrumental in the design of [ALGOL 60](/ALGOL_60). In August 1959, he advocated for the incorporation of recursion and conditional expressions into the language, features that were subsequently adopted. He continued his involvement in shaping international programming standards as a member of the [International Federation for Information Processing](/International_Federation_for_Information_Processing) (IFIP) [Working Group 2.1](/IFIP_Working_Group_2.1), which was responsible for specifying and maintaining ALGOL 60 and [ALGOL 68](/ALGOL_68).

Around 1959, McCarthy conceptualized and invented "garbage collection" methods, a form of automatic [memory management](/Memory_management), to address the memory allocation challenges inherent in Lisp.

During his tenure at [MIT](/MIT), he was a driving force behind the establishment of [Project MAC](/Project_MAC), a pioneering computer research center. Later, at Stanford University, he was instrumental in founding the [Stanford AI Laboratory](/Stanford_AI_Laboratory), which for many years engaged in a spirited and productive rivalry with Project MAC.

McCarthy was a pivotal figure in the development of three of the earliest [time-sharing systems](/Time-sharing): the [Compatible Time-Sharing System](/Compatible_Time-Sharing_System), the [BBN Time-Sharing System](/BBN_Time-Sharing_System), and the [Dartmouth Time-Sharing System](/Dartmouth_Time-Sharing_System). His colleague, [Lester Earnest](/Lester_Earnest), aptly summarized McCarthy's foresight to the [Los Angeles Times](/Los_Angeles_Times): "The Internet would not have happened nearly as soon as it did except for the fact that John initiated the development of time-sharing systems. We keep inventing new names for time-sharing. It came to be called servers ... Now we call it cloud computing. That is still just time-sharing. John started it."

In 1961, McCarthy was among the first to publicly articulate the vision of [utility computing](/Utility_computing). In a speech commemorating MIT's centennial, he posited that [time-sharing](/Time-sharing) technology could evolve into a future where computing power and applications would be accessible as a service, akin to [water](/Water) or [electricity](/Electricity). This concept of a "computer utility" gained considerable traction in the late 1960s, though its prominence waned by the mid-1990s. Nevertheless, the idea has seen a resurgence since 2000 in various forms, including [application service provider](/Application_service_provider) models, [grid computing](/Grid_computing), and [cloud computing](/Cloud_computing).

In 1966, McCarthy and his team at Stanford developed a chess-playing computer program that competed against counterparts in the [Soviet Union](/Soviet_Union). The program, known as Kotok-McCarthy, participated in a series of games, resulting in two losses and two draws for McCarthy's team.

From 1978 to 1986, McCarthy dedicated significant effort to developing the [circumscription](/Circumscription_(logic)) method, a crucial advancement in [non-monotonic reasoning](/Non-monotonic_reasoning), which deals with reasoning under uncertainty and incomplete information.

In 1982, he appears to have conceived the concept of the [space fountain](/Space_fountain), a theoretical structure designed to extend into space, stabilized by the outward force of a continuous stream of pellets propelled from Earth. This innovative idea envisioned a system where payloads could ascend along the conveyor belt of returning pellets.

### Other Activities

McCarthy was a frequent and insightful commentator on global affairs within the [Usenet](/Usenet) forums. His perspectives on sustainability, advocating for the desirability and achievability of human material progress, were articulated on his personal webpage. An avid reader, McCarthy was an optimist and a staunch defender of free speech. His engagements on Usenet, particularly in the rec.arts.books archives, reveal his active participation in discussions and his attendance at r.a.b. reader gatherings, known as rab-fests, in the San Francisco Bay Area. He notably defended the principle of free speech when it involved criticism related to European ethnic jokes at Stanford.

McCarthy deeply understood the significance of mathematics and its education. His [Usenet](/Usenet) signature block ([.sig](/.sig)) often featured the aphorism, "He who refuses to do arithmetic is doomed to talk nonsense," a sentiment echoed by his license plate cover that read, "Do the arithmetic or be doomed to talk nonsense." He mentored and advised 30 PhD graduates during his career.

His 2001 short story, "The Robot and the Baby," offered a humorous exploration of whether robots should possess or simulate emotions, presciently anticipating elements of internet culture and [social networking](/Social_networking) that would become increasingly prominent in the following decades.

### Personal Life

John McCarthy's personal life was marked by three marriages. His second wife, [Vera Watson](/Vera_Watson), was both a programmer and an accomplished mountaineer. Tragically, she perished in 1978 during an attempt to scale [Annapurna I Central](/Annapurna_I_Central) as part of an [all-women expedition](/American_Women%27s_Himalayan_Expedition). He later married [Carolyn Talcott](/Carolyn_Talcott), a fellow computer scientist who also worked at Stanford and later at [SRI International](/SRI_International).

McCarthy publicly declared himself an atheist during a speech on artificial intelligence delivered at [Stanford Memorial Church](/Stanford_Memorial_Church). Having been raised in a [Communist](/Communism) household, his political views evolved significantly after a visit to [Czechoslovakia](/Czechoslovakia) in 1968, in the wake of the [Soviet invasion](/Soviet_invasion_of_Czechoslovakia), leading him to identify as a conservative [Republican](/Republican_Party_(United_States)). He passed away at his home in Stanford on October 24, 2011.

### Philosophy of Artificial Intelligence

In his 1979 article, "Ascribing Mental Qualities to Machines," McCarthy presented a provocative perspective, suggesting that "Machines as simple as [thermostats](/Thermostat) can be said to have beliefs, and having beliefs seems to be a characteristic of most machines capable of problem-solving performance." This assertion sparked a significant debate within the field, most notably eliciting a response from philosopher [John Searle](/John_Searle) in 1980 with his influential [Chinese Room](/Chinese_Room) Argument. Searle countered McCarthy's view, arguing that machines, lacking consciousness, could not genuinely possess beliefs or [intentionality](/Intentionality), even if they could simulate intelligent behavior. This philosophical divergence has fueled extensive discussion and scholarly work, with numerous arguments presented in support of both McCarthy's functionalist approach and Searle's critique.

### Awards and Honors

McCarthy's extraordinary contributions to computer science and artificial intelligence were recognized with a multitude of prestigious awards and honors throughout his career:

*   [Turing Award](/Turing_Award) from the [Association for Computing Machinery](/Association_for_Computing_Machinery) (1971)
*   [Kyoto Prize](/Kyoto_Prize) (1988)
*   United States [National Medal of Science](/National_Medal_of_Science) in Mathematical, Statistical, and Computational Sciences (1990)
*   Inducted as a Fellow of the [Computer History Museum](/Computer_History_Museum) in 1999, "for his co-founding of the fields of Artificial Intelligence (AI) and timesharing systems, and for major contributions to mathematics and computer science."
*   [Benjamin Franklin Medal](/Benjamin_Franklin_Medal_(Franklin_Institute)) in Computer and Cognitive Science from the [Franklin Institute](/Franklin_Institute) (2003)
*   Inducted into [IEEE Intelligent Systems](/IEEE_Intelligent_Systems)' AI's Hall of Fame in 2011, for his "significant contributions to the field of AI and intelligent systems."
*   Recognized as one of the 2012 [Stanford](/Stanford_University) Engineering Heroes.

### Major Publications

McCarthy authored and co-authored numerous seminal papers that shaped the fields of computer science and artificial intelligence:

*   McCarthy, J. 1959. "Programs with Common Sense." In *Proceedings of the Teddington Conference on the Mechanisation of Thought Processes*, 756–91. London: Her Majesty's Stationery Office. (Archived at the [Wayback Machine](/Wayback_Machine))
*   McCarthy, J. 1960. "Recursive functions of symbolic expressions and their computation by machine." *[Communications of the ACM](/Communications_of_the_ACM)* 3(4):184-195. (Archived at the [Wayback Machine](/Wayback_Machine))
*   McCarthy, J. 1963a. "A basis for a mathematical theory of computation." In *Computer Programming and formal systems*. North-Holland.
*   McCarthy, J. 1963b. *Situations, actions, and causal laws*. Technical report, Stanford University.
*   McCarthy, J., and Hayes, P. J. 1969. "Some philosophical problems from the standpoint of artificial intelligence." In *Machine Intelligence 4*, edited by B. Meltzer and D. Michie, 463–502. Edinburgh: Edinburgh University Press. (Archived at the [Wayback Machine](/Wayback_Machine))
*   McCarthy, J. 1977. "Epistemological problems of artificial intelligence." In *[IJCAI](/IJCAI)*, 1038–1044.
*   McCarthy, J (1980). "Circumscription: A form of non-monotonic reasoning." *[Artificial Intelligence](/Artificial_Intelligence_(journal))* 13 (1–2): 23–79. [doi](/Doi_(identifier)):10.1016/0004-3702(80)90011-9.
*   McCarthy, J (1986). "Applications of circumscription to common sense reasoning." *Artificial Intelligence* 28 (1): 89–116. [CiteSeerX](/CiteSeerX_(identifier)) 10.1.1.29.5268. [doi](/Doi_(identifier)):10.1016/0004-3702(86)90032-9.
*   McCarthy, J. 1990. "Generality in artificial intelligence." In *Formalizing Common Sense*, edited by V. Lifschitz, 226–236. Ablex.
*   McCarthy, J. 1993. "Notes on formalizing context." In *[IJCAI](/IJCAI)*, 555–562.
*   McCarthy, J., and Buvac, S. 1997. "Formalizing context: Expanded notes." In *Computing Natural Language*, edited by A. Aliseda, R. van Glabbeek, and D. Westerstahl. Stanford University. (Also available as Stanford Technical Note STAN-CS-TN-94-13.)
*   McCarthy, J. 1998. "Elaboration tolerance." In *Working Papers of the Fourth International Symposium on Logical formalizations of Commonsense Reasoning*, Commonsense-1998.
*   Costello, T., and McCarthy, J. 1999. "Useful counterfactuals." *[Electronic Transactions on Artificial Intelligence](/Electronic_Transactions_on_Artificial_Intelligence)* 3(A):51-76.
*   McCarthy, J. 2002. "Actions and other events in situation calculus." In *Proceedings of KR-2002*, edited by D. Fensel, F. Giunchiglia, D. McGuinness, and M. Williams, 615–628.

